<div id="review_852402177" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/852402177" />
    <a title="Bill Kupersmith" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12460952-bill-kupersmith"><img alt="Bill Kupersmith" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1428792100p2/12460952.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/852402177?book_show_action=true">Dec 20, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bill Kupersmith" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bill Kupersmith" href="/user/show/12460952-bill-kupersmith">Bill Kupersmith</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/9660334-the-cloud-of-unknowing">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12460952-bill-kupersmith?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer852402177" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12510159159474207137">This is a book of spiritual counsel by an anonymous 14th century spiritual director. In mediaeval English a spiritual director would have been called a &quot;ghostly father&quot; (or &quot;ghostly mother&quot; if a woman such as Julian of Norwich). The one being directed would be called a &quot;ghostly friend.&quot; A &quot;ghostly&quot; reader such as myself never actually finishes such books because they have no plot—the &quot;ghostly&quot; realm is timeless. Actually what the author calls &quot;unknowing&quot; is what we Christians refer to as &quot;centri</span>
  <span id="freeText12510159159474207137" style="display:none">This is a book of spiritual counsel by an anonymous 14th century spiritual director. In mediaeval English a spiritual director would have been called a "ghostly father" (or "ghostly mother" if a woman such as Julian of Norwich). The one being directed would be called a "ghostly friend." A "ghostly" reader such as myself never actually finishes such books because they have no plot—the "ghostly" realm is timeless. Actually what the author calls "unknowing" is what we Christians refer to as "centring prayer"—it doesn't differ from Buddhist and Hindu practices that we know as Zen or TM except in the terminology. It is basically a simple means to open your mind entirely to God.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12510159159474207137" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


