<div id="review_678572429" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/678572429" />
    <a title="Chris Elgood" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22203412-chris-elgood"><img alt="Chris Elgood" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442483338p2/22203412.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/678572429?book_show_action=true">Jul 27, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chris Elgood" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chris Elgood" href="/user/show/22203412-chris-elgood">Chris Elgood</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer678572429" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11139182753432269214">It is a significant book, but should be read only by people interested in the mystical tradition of 14th Century Christianity. It is the principal item in a collection of texts published under the same name. The writer is thought to be a monk, devoted to the &quot;work&quot; of contemplation and concerned to counsel a young follower. The core theme is that the work of contemplation requires eradication from the mind of all conscious thought (good or bad) and intense concentration on God - longing desperat</span>
  <span id="freeText11139182753432269214" style="display:none">It is a significant book, but should be read only by people interested in the mystical tradition of 14th Century Christianity. It is the principal item in a collection of texts published under the same name. The writer is thought to be a monk, devoted to the "work" of contemplation and concerned to counsel a young follower. The core theme is that the work of contemplation requires eradication from the mind of all conscious thought (good or bad) and intense concentration on God - longing desperately for Him and beating constantly on the "Cloud of Unknowing" which conceals Him. If this is achieved, God will possibly grant glimpses of Himself and of that divine state that existed before the fall. (As in Genesis.) The meaning is hard to grasp and one feels sympathy for the writer as he tries to explain the unexplainable. Often he finishes an argument and then says, "Don't think that I mean to say THIS. What I really want to say is THAT". The thoughts that the student is supposed to stamp down are so many that the student might ask, "What exactly am I supposed to do, rather than not do? "The writer is so scared that he has been unclear, or that he will be misinterpreted that he tries to prevent his text falling into the hands of those who would read it the wrong way. This is odd for an instructional text. It is a puzzling book, but interesting in that it pushes an idea to the extreme - the idea that there is something "out there" that we might be able to access if we could completely empty our minds of what we think we already know.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11139182753432269214" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


